The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport
		 Thursday, March 18, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Karachi: Pakistans Kiran Baloch shattered the womens world record for the highest Test score by cracking 242 in the first Test against the West Indies at the National Stadium here on Tuesday. Kirans score surpassed the previous best of 214 by Indias Mithali Raj who notched up her double century against England in Taunton in 2001-02.				 																																	Kiran, one of three Pakistani women to have played in England and a life member of the MCC, said she was ecstatic. I am delighted on creating world record and credit this record to all the women players in the world, said Kiran. Its a great moment in womens cricket in Pakistan and I am delighted that such records will give us the due recognition which has been missing, said the 28-year-old from Hyderabad.				 																																	Jaipur: Olympic medal hope Major Rajyavardhan Singh Rathore has roped in former Olympic gold medallist Mark Russel of Australia as his coach. Major Rathore, who recently bagged the gold in prestigious ISSF World Cup in Sydney said here that he would now have two coaches  Italian Luca Marieni and Russel.				 																																	Russel, who retired from active shooting recently, had won the gold in 1996 Atlanta Olympics and the silver in Sydney 2000.				 																																	New Delhi: Mahesh Bhupathi and Max Mirnyi entered the doubles quarter finals at the ATP Masters in Indian Wells, California, on Tuesday. According to information received here, the second-seeded pair beat Martin Garcia and Sebastian Prieto of Argentina 7-5, 6-3. They will meet Spaniards Rafael Nadal and Tommy Robredo in the quarter finals.				 																																	Rio de Janeiro: Ronaldo, who has missed Real Madrids last two games through injury, has been included in Brazils squad for a World Cup qualifier in Paraguay this month.				 																																	Rivaldo, who last month quit Cruzeiro in solidarity with sacked coach Vanderley Luxemburgo, was left out as expected as coach Carlos Alberto Parreira named his squad on Tuesday.				 																																	Brazil are hopeful Ronaldo will be ready to face Paraguay, who lead the South American World Cup qualifying group, in Asuncion on March 31.				 																																	Munich: Two unexploded World War II era bombs were found at the construction site for Munichs new soccer stadium on Tuesday and detonated in a controlled explosion, police said.				 																																	The grenade-style explosives were unearthed outside the stadium, where the opening match of the 2006 World Cup finals in Germany will be held. 				 																																	Police halted traffic on a nearby motorway for about 90 minutes as explosive experts removed the obstacle.				 																																	London: British snooker player Jimmy White was questioned by police on Wednesday on suspicion of having hard drugs, police sources said. Lancashire police said they had arrested a 42-year-old in the northern town of Preston in the early hours of the morning on suspicion of possessing class A drugs. He had been bailed to return on April 21. 				 																																	By that time well have the drug analysed, said a spokeswoman.				 																																	Police sources confirmed his identity as Jimmy White, who had been playing an exhibition match nearby. Sport on ScreenCricket, Sri Lanka vs Australia  second Test Day II live from 9.30 am on TEN Sports 
